Fremantle Prison was built on a land grant of about {{convert|36|acres}} from limestone quarried on-site. A {{convert|15|ft|adj = on}} tall boundary wall encloses the prison grounds, with a gatehouse in the centre of the western wall, facing The Terrace.<ref name="FP buildings" /> Other roads bounding the site are Knutsford Street to the north, [[Hampton Road]] to the east, and Fothergill Street to the south.<ref name="Palassis 2003 Master Plan Background" />{{rp|7}} Cottages, which housed prison workers and officials, are located outside the wall either side of the gatehouse. Inside the walls, the parade ground is located east of the gatehouse. Beyond it is the Main Cell Block<ref name="FP before-after">{{cite web |author1=The Department of Finance – Building Management and Works |title=Before and After Images |url=http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/Cultural_Heritage/beforeandafterimages/Pages/default.aspx |website=Fremantle Prison |publisher=Government of Western Australia |accessdate=10 August 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140513061229/http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/Cultural_Heritage/beforeandafterimages/Pages/default.aspx |archivedate=13 May 2014 |deadurl=no}} {{Cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6TXCFdZxZ |archivedate=23 October 2014}}</ref> at the centre of the site,<ref name="FP buildings" /> which contains two chapels.<ref name="FP chapels">{{cite web |author1=The Department of Finance – Building Management and Works |title=Chapels |url=http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/Functions/venuehire/chapels/Pages/default.aspx |website=Fremantle Prison |publisher=Government of Western Australia |accessdate=10 August 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140204233513/http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/Functions/venuehire/chapels/Pages/default.aspx |archivedate=4 February 2014 |deadurl=no}} {{Cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6TXCzY4z7 |archivedate=23 October 2014}}</ref> North of the main block is New Division, and west of that, in the north-western corner, is the former Women's Prison,<ref name="FP buildings" /> previously the cookhouse, bakehouse and laundry.<ref name="FP womens">{{cite web |author1=The Department of Finance – Building Management and Works |title=Women's Prison |url=http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/Cultural_Heritage/prisonbuildings/womensprison/Pages/default.aspx |website=Fremantle Prison |publisher=Government of Western Australia |accessdate=10 August 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140213171903/http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/Cultural_Heritage/prisonbuildings/womensprison/Pages/default.aspx |archivedate=13 February 2014 |deadurl=no}} {{Cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6TXD4qJHr |archivedate=23 October 2014}}</ref> The hospital building stands in the north-eastern corner, while the former workshops are located in the south-eastern corner, as well as to the north of the gatehouse.<ref name="FP buildings">{{cite web |author1=The Department of Finance – Building Management and Works |title=Prison Buildings |url=http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/Cultural_Heritage/prisonbuildings/Pages/default.aspx |website=Fremantle Prison |publisher=Government of Western Australia |accessdate=10 August 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140513080020/http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/Cultural_Heritage/prisonbuildings/Pages/default.aspx |archivedate=13 May 2014 |deadurl=no}} {{Cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6TXCfH1jD |archivedate=23 October 2014}}</ref> A system of underground tunnels, constructed to provide fresh water from an [[aquifer]], runs under the eastern edge of the site.<ref name="Maritime Museum 2004 tunnels report" />{{rp|2–3}}

=== Buildings ===

==== Houses on The Terrace ====
North of the gatehouse, located at 2, 4, and 6 The Terrace, are cottages built in [[Victorian architecture|Victorian]] style, in contrast to the [[Georgian architecture|Georgian]] style of the other houses.<ref>{{cite web |author1=The Department of Finance – Building Management and Works |title=2, 4 and 6 The Terrace |url=http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/Cultural_Heritage/prisonbuildings/24and6theterrace/Pages/default.aspx |website=Fremantle Prison |publisher=Government of Western Australia |accessdate=10 August 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140213171647/http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/Cultural_Heritage/prisonbuildings/24and6theterrace/Pages/default.aspx |archivedate=13 February 2014 |deadurl=no}} {{Cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6TXDTRrBQ |archivedate=23 October 2014}}</ref> Number 10 is a double-storey house, initially built in 1853 for the chaplain, but taken over by the superintendent in 1878 and later used by the prison administration. An adjoining single-storey at number 12, finished in 1854, was the home of the gatekeeper, located on the north side of the gatehouse.<ref>{{cite web |author1=The Department of Finance – Building Management and Works |title=10 and 12 The Terrace |url=http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/Cultural_Heritage/prisonbuildings/10and12theterrace/Pages/default.aspx |website=Fremantle Prison |publisher=Government of Western Australia |accessdate=10 August 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140213171726/http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/Cultural_Heritage/prisonbuildings/10and12theterrace/Pages/default.aspx |archivedate=13 February 2014 |deadurl=no}} {{Cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6TXDa47go |archivedate=23 October 2014}}</ref> Number 16 The Terrace, south of the gatehouse, is a double-storey house that accommodated first the superintendent, and later the resident magistrate. It remained in use as housing for prison officers until the 1970s.<ref>{{cite web |author1=The Department of Finance – Building Management and Works |title=16 The Terrace |url=http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/Cultural_Heritage/prisonbuildings/16theterrace/Pages/default.aspx |website=Fremantle Prison |publisher=Government of Western Australia |accessdate=10 August 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140213171750/http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/Cultural_Heritage/prisonbuildings/16theterrace/Pages/default.aspx |archivedate=13 February 2014 |deadurl=no}} {{Cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6TXDh7JX1 |archivedate=23 October 2014}}</ref> Number 18, the southernmost house on The Terrace, and number 8, the northernmost of the initial buildings, both featured two sitting rooms, three bedrooms, and two dressing rooms, as well as a kitchen, [[water closet]] and shed, but with mirrored layouts. Number 18 was expanded with additions built in the 1890s.<ref>{{cite web |author1=The Department of Finance – Building Management and Works |title=18 The Terrace |url=http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/Cultural_Heritage/prisonbuildings/18theterrace/Pages/default.aspx |website=Fremantle Prison |publisher=Government of Western Australia |accessdate=10 August 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140213171806/http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/Cultural_Heritage/prisonbuildings/18theterrace/Pages/default.aspx |archivedate=13 February 2014 |deadurl=no}} {{Cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6TXDml2zD |archivedate=23 October 2014}}</ref>

==== Gatehouse ====
The gatehouse and associated entry complex was constructed between 1854 and 1855 using convict labour. It was designed by Royal Engineer and Comptroller General [[Edmund Henderson]], and constructed out of limestone.<ref name="FP Gatehouse" /> The gatehouse has two towers either side of a narrow gate, reminiscent of those found in 13th century English castles or walled cities.<ref name=ausmed>{{cite web |title=Fremantle Prison Gatehouse, Fremantle, Western Australia |url=http://ausmed.arts.uwa.edu.au/items/show/159 |website=Medievalism in Australian Cultural Memory |publisher=University of Western Australia |accessdate=23 October 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110412233745/http://ausmed.arts.uwa.edu.au/items/show/159|archivedate=12 April 2011 |deadurl=no}} {{Cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6TWuH3R9g |archivedate=23 October 2014}}</ref> Iron that had been scavenged from shipwrecks was used to make the gate, while the clock at the top of the structure was imported from England.<ref name="Ayris 2003 Brief History">{{cite book |last1=Ayris |first1=Cyril |author-link1=Cyril Ayris |title=Fremantle Prison: A Brief History |year=2003 |origyear=First published 1995 |publisher=Cyril Ayris Freelance |isbn=0-9581882-1-1 }}</ref>{{rp|26}} As the main entrance, the gatehouse has remained a significant feature and landmark; since the closure of the prison, it has housed a café and office areas.<ref name="FP Gatehouse">{{cite web |author1=The Department of Finance – Building Management and Works |title=Gatehouse |url=http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/Cultural_Heritage/prisonbuildings/Gatehouse/Pages/default.aspx |website=Fremantle Prison |publisher=Government of Western Australia |accessdate=10 August 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140213171923/http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/Cultural_Heritage/prisonbuildings/Gatehouse/Pages/default.aspx |archivedate=13 February 2014 |deadurl=no}} {{Cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6TXDymX9Y |archivedate=23 October 2014}}</ref> Restoration was carried out in 2005, preserving the original stone facade and removing non-original rendering.<ref name="ausmed" />

==== Main Cell Block ====
[[File:FremantlePrisonCell.jpg|left|thumb|upright|A re-creation of typical 1855 cell accommodation]]
Little-changed since its construction in the 1850s by convicts, the Main Cell Block was designed to hold up to 1000 prisoners. The central, four-storey high cell block is flanked on either end by large dormitory wards, called the Association Rooms. Here, as many as 80 men slept in hammocks, either as a reward for good behaviour or because they would soon receive their [[ticket of leave]]. In contrast, the cramped cells measured just {{convert|7|by|4|ft|spell = in}}. Although each cell initially had a basin connected to running water, the installation was before the advent of [[S-bend]]s; the smells coming up the pipes led to their removal by the 1860s. Following a [[Royal Commission]], the cells were enlarged by removing a dividing wall from between two cells. Electric lighting was installed in the 1920s, but there were never any toilets – buckets were used for the duration of the prison's operation. Since the prison's closure, six cells have been restored to represent the varying living conditions at different times in the prison's history.<ref name="FP Main Block">{{cite web |author1 = The Department of Finance – Building Management and Works|title = Main Cell Block|url = http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/Cultural_Heritage/prisonbuildings/MainCellBlock/Pages/default.aspx|website = Fremantle Prison|publisher = Government of Western Australia|accessdate = 10 August 2014|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140213171939/http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/Cultural_Heritage/prisonbuildings/MainCellBlock/Pages/default.aspx|archivedate = 13 February 2014|deadurl = no}} {{Cite additional archived pages |archiveurl = http://www.webcitation.org/6TXE7UVTi|archivedate = 23 October 2014}}</ref> The main block also houses the [[gallows]], [[solitary confinement]] cells, and two chapels – [[Anglican]] and [[Catholic Church|Catholic]].<ref name="FP chapels" /><ref name="Ayris 2003 Brief History" />{{rp|46}}

==== New Division ====
Fremantle Prison's New Division building was constructed between 1904 and 1907, as a response to overcrowding. It also allowed prison administrators to implement the "[[separate system]]", whereby prisoners were completely isolated for the first three months of their sentence. A [[panopticon]] in the exercise yard was initially used to facilitate this concept during the prisoners' hour of exercise each day. The system was not successful, and considered a dated prisoner management strategy, leading to its removal within five years. New Division was the first building to have electricity, with underground wiring. During World War II, the Australian Army appropriated the division, to keep their prisoners separate from the main population. In 1994 the building was retrofitted to cater for offices, small business premises, and meeting rooms.<ref name="FP New Division">{{cite web |author1=The Department of Finance – Building Management and Works |title=New Division |url=http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/Cultural_Heritage/prisonbuildings/newdivision/Pages/default.aspx |website=Fremantle Prison |publisher=Government of Western Australia |accessdate=10 August 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140213171842/http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/Cultural_Heritage/prisonbuildings/newdivision/Pages/default.aspx |archivedate=13 February 2014 |deadurl=no}} {{Cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6TXETG4j8 |archivedate=23 October 2014}}</ref>

==== Women's Prison ====
The north-western complex was originally a service area with a cookhouse, bakehouse and laundry, built in the 1850s. A place for women prisoners was needed following the closure of [[Perth Gaol]] and the transfer of prisoners to Fremantle. The buildings were converted to a prison, and a wall built around them, creating Western Australia's first separate prison for women. Population and crime growth led to them being extended in the 1890s and 1910s. The construction of [[Bandyup Women's Prison]] saw Fremantle's Women's Prison close in 1970, with the space used for education and assessment until the main prison's closure in 1991.<ref name="FP womens" />

==== Hospital ====
Built between 1857 and 1859, the hospital was a crucial component of Fremantle Prison. Public works during the convict era relied on convict labour, which could only be provided if the convicts were healthy. From 1886 to 1903, medical services were relocated to the main cell block, with the former building used to keep invalids and female prisoners. The hospital was refurbished and reopened in 1904. It subsequently remained in continuous operation until the prison's closure in 1991.<ref>{{cite web |author1=The Department of Finance – Building Management and Works |title=Hospital |url=http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/Cultural_Heritage/prisonbuildings/hospital/Pages/default.aspx |website=Fremantle Prison |publisher=Government of Western Australia |accessdate=10 August 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140213171822/http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/Cultural_Heritage/prisonbuildings/hospital/Pages/default.aspx |archivedate=13 February 2014 |deadurl=no}} {{Cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6TXFK5sxZ |archivedate=23 October 2014}}</ref>

==== Workshops ====
The original workshop was a blacksmith's shop, one of the first buildings to be constructed on the prison site. Later known as the East Workshops, other workshops included carpenter's, plumber's and painter's, a printing office, and from the 1850s, a metal shop.<ref>{{cite web |author1=The Department of Finance – Building Management and Works |title=East Workshops |url=http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/Cultural_Heritage/prisonbuildings/eastworkshops/Pages/default.aspx |website=Fremantle Prison |publisher=Government of Western Australia |accessdate=10 August 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140213171956/http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/Cultural_Heritage/prisonbuildings/eastworkshops/Pages/default.aspx |archivedate=13 February 2014 |deadurl=no}} {{Cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6TXFKf2gI |archivedate=23 October 2014}}</ref> The West Workshops were built at the start of the twentieth century, providing more work for prisoners through a paint shop, mat maker, shoe maker, book binder and tailor shop.<ref>{{cite web |author1=The Department of Finance – Building Management and Works |title=West Workshops |url=http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/Cultural_Heritage/prisonbuildings/westworkshops/Pages/default.aspx |website=Fremantle Prison |publisher=Government of Western Australia |accessdate=10 August 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140213172013/http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/Cultural_Heritage/prisonbuildings/westworkshops/Pages/default.aspx |archivedate=13 February 2014 |deadurl=no}} {{Cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6TXFMvbn2 |archivedate=23 October 2014}}</ref>
In 1993 the four northern workshops were adapted for use as [[technical and further education|TAFE]] art workshops.<ref name=AHDB />

=== Tunnels ===
[[File:Fremantleprisontunnels.JPG|left|thumb|View inside the tunnels]]
In the 1850s, shafts were sunk into the [[limestone]] bedrock to provide the prison with fresh water from an [[aquifer]], and a tank was installed in 1874 to offer the town of Fremantle an alternative water supply. Prisoners worked a pump to fill the tank, which was connected to the jetties through [[Gravity feed|gravity-fed]] pipes.<ref name="Maritime Museum 2004 tunnels report">{{cite book |last1=Coley |first1=Beresford |last2=McCarthy |first2=Michael |last3=Richards |first3=Vicki |title=Watercraft In The Old Fremantle Prison Tunnels: Maritime Heritage Site Inspection Report |year=2004 |publisher=Department of Maritime Archaeology, Western Australian Maritime Museum |url=http://museum.wa.gov.au/maritime-archaeology-db/sites/default/files/no._191_prison_watercraft.pdf |format=PDF |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140929115814/http://museum.wa.gov.au/maritime-archaeology-db/sites/default/files/no._191_prison_watercraft.pdf |archivedate=29 September 2014 |deadurl=yes}} {{Cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6TWluhcia |archivedate=23 October 2014}}</ref>{{rp|2–3}} In 1896, a town reservoir was constructed on Swanbourne Street, fed from the prison by a [[triple-expansion]] steam-driven pump that could take more than {{convert|1000000|impgal|ML|order=flip|abbr=off}} per day from the prison tunnels. Prisoners, relieved of manual pumping, were employed to supply wood and stoke boilers.<ref name="Maritime Museum 2004 tunnels report" />{{rp|2–3}} The tunnels were closed in 1910,<ref name="TheWest tunnels">{{cite news |last1=Amalfi |first1=Carmelo |title=Jail Tunnels Open To Public |work=The West Australian |date=6 April 2004 |page=3}}</ref> though the groundwater continued to be used for the prison's gardens. In 1989, oil leaking from nearby tanks contaminated the water; however, the pollution was cleared by 1996 through [[bioremediation]].<ref name="Maritime Museum 2004 tunnels report" />{{rp|3}} The tunnels were re-opened in mid-2005, and had been refurbished within a year to improve the experience for visitors.<ref name="The West 2006 tunnel work">{{cite news |last1=Chandler |first1=Ainslie |title=Fremantle Tunnels Work A Challenge |work=The West Australian |date=21 June 2006 |page=61}}</ref>

== History ==
{{Main article|History of Fremantle Prison}}

=== 19th century ===
While the Swan River Colony was established as a "free settlement"<ref name="Appleyard 1979">{{cite book |first1=Reginald T |last1=Appleyard |first2=Toby |last2=Manford |year=1979 |title=The Beginning: European Discovery and Early Settlement of Swan River Western Australia |location=Nedlands, Western Australia |publisher=University of Western Australia Press |isbn=0-85564-146-0}}</ref> (unlike the [[penal colonies]] on the east coast), by the 1840s demand for cheap labour overcame an early reluctance, and the colony agreed to accept some convicts from Britain. The arrival of the first convict ship ''[[Scindian]]'' on 2 June 1850 was unexpected, as a sailing ship that had been sent ahead had been blown off-course. The colony's [[Round House]] jail was full, so the 75 convicts had to be left on the ship<ref name="Ayris 2003 Brief History" />{{rp|18–20}} until a temporary prison was built. Comptroller General of Convicts Edward Henderson looked for a place to build a permanent convict establishment, and ultimately settled on the current site, on a hill overlooking Fremantle.<ref name="Ayris 2003 Brief History" />{{rp|21–22}}

[[File:FremantlePrisonMainCellBlockMap.jpg|thumb|right|Main Cell Block internal arrangement]]
[[File:FremantlePrisonHenry Wray.jpg|thumb|1859 [[Watercolour painting|watercolour]] of the Main Cell Block, by Henry Wray]]
The design for Fremantle Prison was based on the [[Pentonville Prison]] in Britain, but with diagonal cell blocks replaced with a four-storey linear structure, which would be the longest, tallest prison cell block in the southern hemisphere.<ref name="FP building establishment">{{cite web |author1=The Department of Finance – Building Management and Works |title=Building The Convict Establishment |url=http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/schoolgroups/educationalresources/Documents/FP%20Building%20the%20Convict%20Establishment.pdf |format=PDF |publisher=Government of Western Australia |accessdate=10 August 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140205213132/http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/schoolgroups/educationalresources/Documents/FP%20Building%20the%20Convict%20Establishment.pdf |archivedate=5 February 2014 |deadurl=no}} {{Cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6TXGGPGvP |archivedate=23 October 2014}}</ref>{{rp|2}} Construction began in 1851,<ref name="Ayris 2003 Brief History" />{{rp|22}} and work rapidly progressed following the arrival of the Royal Engineers later that year. They trained convicts to work with limestone, which was quarried on-site.<ref name="FP building establishment" />{{rp|4}} The first priority was the construction of accommodation for Henderson and the prison warders, to relieve the expense of paying for private lodging.<ref name="FP building establishment" />{{rp|3}}

The prison walls were constructed between 1853 and 1855, while the gatehouse and associated entry complex was built in 1854 and 1855.<ref name="FP building establishment" />{{rp|4–5}} Construction of the southern half of the Main Cell Block began in 1853 and was finished in 1855, with prisoners transferred from the temporary prison on 1 June 1855.<ref name="FP building establishment" />{{rp|7}} Construction of the northern wing followed. The [[Crimean War]] saw the Royal Engineers recalled, leaving only one of their number, [[Henry Wray]], to oversee the building's construction, which was completed by the end of 1859.<ref name="FP building establishment" />{{rp|8}}

During [[Convict era of Western Australia|Western Australia's convict era]], the prison was known as the Convict Establishment, and was used for prisoners transported from Britain. Longer term locally-sentenced prisoners were also held there from 1858, at a cost to the colonial government.<ref name="Stevenson 1983 In the 1890s">{{cite thesis |last=Stevenson |first=Lynne |title=Fremantle Prison in the 1890s |date=1983 |url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/18671939 |degree=M.A. |publisher=University of Western Australia}}</ref>{{rp|20–21}} In 1868, [[penal transportation]] to Western Australia ceased, and the number of convicts in the colony gradually declined, down to 83 in the mid-1880s.<ref name="Ayris 2003 Brief History" />{{rp|45–46}} Due to the great expense of sending these convicts back to Britain, the authorities there negotiated with the colonial government to relinquish jurisdiction over them, as well as the prison complex – demolition was considered too expensive.<ref name="Ayris 2003 Brief History" />{{rp|45–46}} Early negotiations had broken down, but were restarted in August 1883.<ref name="Stevenson 1983 In the 1890s" />{{rp|24–25}} After one and a half years, a compromise was reached, and the transfer was finalised on 31 March 1886.<ref name="Stevenson 1983 In the 1890s" />{{rp|25–26}}

Once the prison came under the control of the colonial government, it was renamed Fremantle Prison.<ref name="Ayris 2003 Brief History" /> All prisoners in Perth Gaol were transferred to Fremantle, and from 1887 female prisoners were also imprisoned there, in their own separate section.<ref name="Ayris 2003 Brief History" />{{rp|45–46}} The [[Western Australian gold rushes]] of the 1890s resulted in strong economic growth, and a massive increase in population: doubling from almost 50,000 in 1891 to more than 100,000 by 1895, and to 184,000 by 1901.<ref name=CCWA>{{cite web |url=http://www.constitutionalcentre.wa.gov.au/ResearchAndSeminarPapers/LaunchingTheShip/Pages/TheGoldrush.aspx |title=The Goldrush |work=Launching the Ship of State: A Constitutional History of Western Australia |first=Mathew |last=Trinca |year=1997 |publisher=Centre for Western Australian History, University of Western Australia |via=The Constitutional Centre of Western Australia |accessdate=9 September 2004 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140909031011/http://www.constitutionalcentre.wa.gov.au/ResearchAndSeminarPapers/LaunchingTheShip/Pages/TheGoldrush.aspx |archivedate=9 September 2004 |deadurl=no}} {{cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=http://pandora.nla.gov.au/pan/12506/20120821-1029/www.ccentre.wa.gov.au/researchandseminarpapers/launchingtheship/pages/thegoldrush.aspx |archivedate=21 August 2012}}</ref> This influx included desperate, dishonest people, from elsewhere in Australia and overseas, and Fremantle Prison was soon overcrowded.<ref name="Ayris 2003 Brief History" />{{rp|46}}

{{Wikisource|Report of the Commission Appointed to inquire into the Penal System of the Colony|Report of the 1898 Royal Commission}}
The 1890s also saw a growing public unease with the treatment of prisoners.<ref name="Ayris 2003 Brief History" />{{rp|46–49}} In September 1898  a Royal Commission was established by the Governor of Western Australia to investigate the colony's penal system.<ref name="Stevenson 1983 In the 1890s" />{{rp|150}} The commission heard evidence from almost 240 witnesses,<ref name="Stevenson 1983 In the 1890s" />{{rp|159}} including a range of prisoners.<ref name="Ayris 2003 Brief History" />{{rp|46–49}} Three reports were made between December 1898 and June 1899, dealing with the most recognisable and prominent issues including classification, sentencing, punishments, and diet. In particular, they considered the philosophy of the prison system – the causes of crime, as well as the types of punishments and their justifications – and in light of this, the practicality of various reform proposals.<ref name="Stevenson 1983 In the 1890s" />{{rp|160}}

=== Early 20th century ===
[[File:Freo prison WMAU gnangarra-108.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Three Division for "long sentenced and habitual prisoners"<ref name="Georgiou 1995 Work and reform" />{{rp|12}}]]
Within a year of the enquiry, almost 100 cells had been enlarged by knocking down the inner wall between two cells, and a classification system was introduced. Internal walls were constructed in the main block, creating four separate divisions.<ref name="Georgiou 1995 Work and reform">{{cite thesis |last1=Georgiou |first1=Natasha |others=For Anne Brake, Curator, Fremantle Prison |title=Work and Reform in Fremantle Prison 1898–1912 |type=History Research Essay |date=4 December 1995 |publisher=University of Western Australia |url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/14682051 |accessdate=25 September 2014 }}</ref>{{rp|12–13}} Following the urgings of the prison Superintendent George and various official enquiries, new workshops were built to provide increased useful employment for prisoners. Five spaces were designed for tailors, bookbinders, shoemakers, mat makers and painters.<ref name="AHDB">{{cite web |author1=Department of the Environment|title=Fremantle Prison (former), 1 The Terrace, Fremantle, WA, Australia |url=http://www.environment.gov.au/cgi-bin/ahdb/search.pl?mode=place_detail;place_id=105762 |website=Australian Heritage Database |publisher=Australian Government |accessdate=13 September 2014 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6TWju00IC |archivedate=23 October 2014 |deadurl=no}} {{cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141023100602/http://www.webcitation.org/6TWju00IC |archivedate=23 October 2014}}</ref>

New regulations for prison officers were published in the Government Gazette in 1902, and a new Prisons Act was passed in 1903. While in theory the passing of the Act should have resulted in significant prison reform, this did not eventuate. The legislation left much of the changes to executive regulation, at the discretion of the governor, and was described by the media as a feeble document.<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart">{{cite thesis |degree=Ph.D |last1=Megahey |first1=Norman |publisher=Murdoch University |title=A Community Apart: A History of Fremantle Prison, 1898–1991 |year=2000 | url=http://researchrepository.murdoch.edu.au/4082/2/02Whole.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=23 September 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110415210953/http://researchrepository.murdoch.edu.au/4082/2/02Whole.pdf |archivedate=15 April 2011 |deadurl=no}} {{Cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6TXGvSc2i |archivedate=23 October 2014}}</ref>{{rp|48–51}}

New Division, completed in 1907 and occupied in 1908, resulted from the 1899 Commissioners' report recommending a modified version of the separate system.<ref name="AHDB" /> The new division was similar in design to Henderson's 1850s structure,<ref name="AHDB" /> but was constructed in an L-shape, was only three stories tall, and had electric lighting.<ref name="Ayris 2003 Brief History" />{{rp|50}} It also differed in its use from the main cell block.  Unlike occupants of the earlier building, prisoners remained continuously in their cells except when exercising in separate yards, watched panopticon-style<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hamilton |first1=Jen |editor1-last=Hocken |editor1-first=Tim |title=From Behind Bars |journal=Australian Construction Focus |date=June 2011 |page=40 |url=http://www.constructioninfocus.com.au/index.php/2011/06/20/fremantle-prison/ |accessdate=25 September 2014 <!--|alternate-url=http://www.constructioninfocus.com.au/mag/June2011/index.html#?page=40 -->|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6SqKGD5bv |archivedate=25 September 2014 |deadurl=no |publisher=Focus Media Group |location=Sydney, New South Wales}}</ref> by a warder in a central tower.<ref name="AHDB" />

{{Wikisource|The West Australian/1911/05/10/Fremantle Prison|Report of the 1911 Royal Commission {{small|(as republished in ''The West Australian'')}}}}
In 1911 another Royal Commission investigation into Fremantle Prison recommended closing the facility. Its report was ignored by the state government, which was more concerned with building infrastructure such as roads and schools than the plight of its prisoners.<ref name="Stokes 1968 Human geography thesis" />{{rp|4}} However, there was a rapid change in prison policy, with the appointment of a superintendent, Hugh Hann, who had recent English and colonial experience, and the election of a [[Scaddan Ministry|Labor government]] with members interested in penal reform. One immediate result was the dismantling of the separate system at Fremantle Prison and the demolition of the separate exercise yards in 1912.<ref name=AHDB />

Fremantle Prison was partially used as a [[military prison]] during both world wars – for the detention of military personnel, as well as an internment centre.<ref name=AHDB /> From 1940 until 1946,<ref name="Stokes 1968 Human geography thesis" /><ref name="FP timeline">{{cite web |author1=The Department of Finance – Building Management and Works |title=Fremantle Prison Timeline |url=http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/History/fremantleprisontimeline/Pages/default.aspx |website=Fremantle Prison |publisher=Government of Western Australia |accessdate=16 September 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140822134006/http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/History/fremantleprisontimeline/Pages/default.aspx |archivedate=22 August 2014 |deadurl=no}} {{Cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6TXH0QldY |archivedate=23 October 2014}}</ref> it was one of more than 50 military prisons across Australia holding a combined total of more than 12,000 [[enemy alien]]s and [[prisoners of war]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Young |first1=Matt |last2=Chang |first2=Charis |title=The Forgotten History of Australia's Prisoner of War Camps |url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/anzac-centenary/the-forgotten-history-of-australias-prisoner-of-war-camps/story-fnmeodwa-1226895841822?nk=edc4622cf45619e2aba33d81ce552f11 |accessdate=29 October 2014 |agency=News.com.au |publisher=Herald Sun |location=Melbourne, VIC |date=25 April 2014 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6TftjshfH|archivedate=29 October 2014 |deadurl=no}}</ref> Fremantle accommodated up to 400 military prisoners and up to 160 civilian prisoners by October 1945.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article78483322 |title=Army Controls Most Of Fremantle Gaol |newspaper=[[Daily News (Perth, Western Australia)|The Daily News]] |location=Perth |date=9 October 1945 |accessdate=29 October 2014 |page=7 |edition=Edition: City Final |via=Trove (National Library of Australia)}}</ref> The World War II takeover necessitated the commissioning of Barton's Mill Prison in 1942.<ref name="Stokes 1968 Human geography thesis" />{{rp|4}}

=== 20th century reform ===
Prison outstations were established as part of the reforms in the 20th century,<ref name="Saunders 1960 Prison system">{{cite thesis |last1 = Saunders|first1 = J|title = Development Of The Prison System In Western Australia, 1829–1960|publisher = Graylands Teachers College|date = 1960|url = http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/12700478}}</ref>{{rp|26}} and to reduce the overcrowding at Fremantle.<ref name="Stokes 1968 Human geography thesis" />{{rp|4}} [[Pardelup Prison Farm]] opened in 1927, near Mount Barker,<ref name="Stokes 1968 Human geography thesis" />{{rp|4}} while Barton's Mill, though planned to be a temporary measure, remained open as a prison after World War II.<ref name="Stokes 1968 Human geography thesis" />{{rp|4}}  Significant reform to Western Australia's prison system did not begin until the 1960s, lagging behind those which occurred elsewhere in Australia and the world after World War II.<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|56}} Seven new prisons were opened between 1960 and 1971,<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|57}} and in 1970, female prisoners and staff were moved from Fremantle to the new Bandyup Women's Prison.<ref name="AHDB" /> New legislation regarding probation, parole, and convicted drunkards was also introduced, which provided alternatives to imprisonment. With these new arrangements, and more variety in prisons and prison types, a classification board was set up in 1963 to assess prisoners.<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|57}}

{{Reduced pull quote|right|a place for rehabilitation and re-education&nbsp;... where people can retain their identity and, if necessary, create a new identity|Comptroller General Colin Campbell's view of prisons, 1966<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|58}}}}
The appointment of Colin Campbell as comptroller general in 1966 fostered substantial changes within Fremantle Prison itself.<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|58}} One of his first changes was to clear the classification committee's backlog of prisoners awaiting assessment. Campbell also established an officer training school, as well as an assessment centre to evaluate new prisoners.<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|58–59}} Work release and community service programs were also introduced, along with training programs, social workers and welfare officers.<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|59–61}} Within the midst of Campbell's reforms, the Prisons Department was renamed the Department of Corrections in 1971,<ref name="SRO Dept">{{cite web |author1=State Records Office |title=Agency Detail: Department of Corrections |url=http://aeon.sro.wa.gov.au/Investigator/Details/Agency_Detail.asp?Id=216 |website=AEON (Archives Explored Online) |publisher=Government of Western Australia |accessdate=2 October 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141002045456/http://aeon.sro.wa.gov.au/Investigator/Details/Agency_Detail.asp?Id=216 |archivedate=2 October 2014 |deadurl=no |date=23 August 2004}} {{Cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6TXHG9SdE |archivedate=23 October 2014}}</ref> restructured, and the position of comptroller general was replaced with director of the department.<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|61}}

In 1972 a Royal Commission was appointed to investigate mistreatment of and discrimination against Aboriginal prisoners.<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|18}} Its 1973 report found that there was not "any appreciable discrimination",<ref name="Jones 1973 Royal Commission">{{cite book |last1=Jones |first1=Robert Edmund |title=Report of the Royal Commission upon Various Allegations of Assaults on or Brutality to Prisoners in Fremantle Prison, and of Discrimination against Aboriginal or Part-Aboriginal Prisoners Therein, and upon Certain Other Matters Touching that Prison, its Inmates and Staff |date=14 March 1973 |publisher=Government Printer |location=Western Australia |isbn=978-0-7244-5477-8 |url=http://www.parliament.wa.gov.au/intranet/libpages.nsf/WebFiles/RC+1973/$FILE/0002116.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314095320/http://www.parliament.wa.gov.au/intranet/libpages.nsf/WebFiles/RC+1973/$FILE/0002116.pdf |archivedate=14 March 1973 |deadurl=no |via=[[Parliament of Western Australia]] Library }}</ref>{{rp|161}} however, [[racial stereotype]]s are present throughout the report, and the testimony of Aboriginal prisoners was considered unreliable.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Harris |first1=Mark |editor1-last=Bird |editor1-first=Greta |editor2-last=Martin |editor2-first=Gary |editor3-last=Nielsen |editor3-first=Jennifer |chapter=Deconstructing the Royal Commission – Representations of "Aboriginality" in the Royal Commission into Aboriginal Deaths in Custody |date=1996 |publisher=Federation Press |title=Majah: Indigenous Peoples And The Law |location=Sydney |isbn=1-86287-197-3 |page=195 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cG3Pflz3dVkC&pg=PA195 |accessdate=5 November 2014}}</ref> The report also made recommendations regarding various aspects of prison life, including additional, independent, trained welfare officers.<ref name="Jones 1973 Royal Commission" />{{rp|174}}

William Kidston succeeded Campbell in 1977, and oversaw a shift in policy from "paternalistic rehabilitation"<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|62}} of prisoners to merely providing opportunities for rehabilitation.<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|61–62}} A new Prisons Act was passed in 1981, which updated the 1903 Act with modern philosophies and practices.<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|63}} This act was, however, slanted towards prisoner management and safety, and the department was at the same time renamed the Prisons Department once more, to emphasise imprisonment as its primary responsibility.<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|65–67}} Ian Hill became Director of the Prisons Department in 1983, and reorganised the department several times, striving for increased efficiency.<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|67}} Whilst the changes of the 1980s were effective throughout most of Western Australia's prison system, the culture of Fremantle Prison was resistant to change.<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|68–9}} Growing prisoner discontent eventually culminated in the [[Fremantle Prison riot|1988 prison riot]],<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|68}} investigated by an official enquiry later that year.<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|18}}

=== Closure and subsequent use ===
The state government made the decision to decommission Fremantle Prison in 1983,<ref name="Kumar 2009 Convict Heritage Tourism" />{{rp|203}} but it remained in operation until 30 November 1991.<ref name=AHDB /> Prisoners were moved to a new metropolitan maximum security prison at [[Casuarina Prison|Casuarina]]. There were divergent views in the community over the site's future, whether it should be preserved or redeveloped. The ultimate decision was for conservation of the prison, but allowing for the buildings to be adapted for reuse by the community.<ref name="Kumar 2009 Convict Heritage Tourism" />{{rp|203}}

The Fremantle Prison Trust was established in 1992 to advise the [[Minister for Works (Western Australia)|Minister for Works]]<ref name="Palassis 2003 Master Plan Background">{{cite book |author1=Palassis Architects |others=Prepared for the Department of Housing and Works, Government of Western Australia |chapter=Background |title=Fremantle Prison Heritage Precinct Master Plan |date=July 2003 |chapter-url=http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/About_Us/visionandmasterplan/Documents/0230.647.DHW-GG%20Sect%201.pdf |chapter-format=PDF | accessdate=3 December 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140604011838/http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/About_Us/visionandmasterplan/Documents/0230.647.DHW-GG%20Sect%201.pdf |archivedate=4 June 2014 |deadurl=no}} {{Cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6UWR2xAhp |archivedate=2 December 2014}}</ref> on the management of the site.<ref name=AHDB /> Various new uses were found for different parts of the prison, including [[wedding]] services in the chapels,<ref name="FP chapels" /> the Coastal Business Centre in New Division,<ref name="FP New Division" /> and the [[Fremantle Children's Literature Centre]] in the hospital;<ref name="Bosworth 2004 Convict Fremantle" />{{rp|89}} the prison also became a tourist attraction. A private company,<ref name=AHDB /> the Fremantle Prison Guardians,<ref name="Palmer 1997 graffiti" />{{rp|111}} organised the tourist operation for ten years under contract, until the end of 2001; subsequently, the state government took control.<ref name=AHDB /> A [[hostel]] providing short-stay accommodation in the Women's Prison opened in May 2015.<ref name="Sparvell Backpackers Delight">{{cite news|last1=Sparvell|first1=Ray|title=Backpackers Delight: Night in Fremantle Prison Cell Never Looked So Good|url=http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/your-perth/backpackers-delight-night-in-fremantle-prison-cell-never-looked-so-good-20150130-132bi7.html|accessdate=8 April 2015|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=30 January 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150408081424/http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/your-perth/backpackers-delight-night-in-fremantle-prison-cell-never-looked-so-good-20150130-132bi7.html|archivedate=8 April 2015 |deadurl=no}} {{cite archives |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6XdCoIxCj |archivedate=8 April 2015}}</ref><ref name="Barnes A Night Inside">{{cite news |last1=Barnes |first1=Candice |title=A Night Inside a Cell at Historic (and Spooky) Fremantle Prison |url=http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/your-perth/a-night-inside-a-cell-at-historic-and-spooky-fremantle-prison-20150518-gh40av.html |accessdate=1 June 2015 |newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=18 May 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150601023744/http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/your-perth/a-night-inside-a-cell-at-historic-and-spooky-fremantle-prison-20150518-gh40av.html |archivedate=1 June 2015 |deadurl=no}} {{cite archives |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6YwzTHtMO |archivedate=1 June 2015}}</ref>

== Staff and prisoners ==
{{Main article|Staff and prisoners of Fremantle Prison}}

=== Administration ===
{{further|Comptroller General of Convicts (Western Australia)}}
[[File:EdmundHenderson.jpg|thumb|upright|Comptroller General Edmund Henderson]]
Western Australia's first comptroller general of convicts, Edmund Henderson,<ref name="Hasluck 1959/1991 Unwilling emigrants">{{cite book |last1=Hasluck |first1=Alexandra |authorlink1=Alexandra Hasluck |title=Unwilling Emigrants |date=1991 |origyear=First published: Melbourne: Oxford University Press, 1959 |publisher=Fremantle Arts Centre Press |location=South Fremantle, Western Australia |isbn=0-949206-94-6 |url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/version/6189942}}</ref>{{rp|56}} administered the convict establishment for thirteen years.<ref name="Battye 1924 WA: A history">{{cite book | last1=Battye |first1=James Sykes |author-link1=James Battye |title=Western Australia: A History from its Discovery to the Inauguration of the Commonwealth |date=1924 |publisher=The Clarendon Press |location=Oxford, England |url=http://gutenberg.net.au/ebooks05/0500301h.html |accessdate=10 October 2014 |via=[[Project Gutenberg Australia]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140702211241/http://gutenberg.net.au/ebooks05/0500301h.html |archivedate=2 July 2014 |deadurl=no}} {{Cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6TXKPsgWt |archivedate=23 October 2014}}</ref> The primary responsibilities of the comptroller general were to "direct convict labour and be responsible for convict discipline".<ref name="Bosworth 2004 Convict Fremantle" />{{rp|30}} With the transfer of Fremantle Prison to the colonial government in 1886, the role of the comptroller was replaced by that of the [[sheriff]],<ref name="Kimberley 1897 History WA">{{cite book |last1=Kimberly |first1=Warren Bert |title-link=s:History of West Australia|title=History of West Australia: A narrative of her past together with biographies of her leading men |others={{icon|Wikisource}} |date=1897 |publisher=F. W. Niven & Co. |location=Melbourne, Victoria |chapter=Chapter XVII – Transportation Ceases; North-West; An Election: 1861–1868 |via=[[Wikisource]]}}</ref>{{rp|270}} responsible for all of the prisons in the colony.<ref name="Saunders 1960 Prison system" />{{rp|15}} The position of comptroller general was recreated, with duties split off from the sheriff's office, in early 1911.<ref name="Saunders 1960 Prison system" />{{rp|23}} In 1971, the Prisons Department was renamed the Department of Corrections,<ref name="SRO Dept" /> restructured, and the position of comptroller general was replaced with director of the department.<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|61}} While the comptroller, sheriff, or director was responsible for the overall convict or prison system, largely centred around Fremantle Prison,<ref name="Megahey 2007 Rehab 1966-91">{{cite journal |last1=Megahey |first1=Norman |title=The Rise and Fall of Rehabilitation in the Western Australian Prison System, 1966–1991 |journal=Studies in Western Australian History |date=2007 |volume=25 |pages=57–74 |issn=0314-7525 |url=http://0-search.informit.com.au.catalogue.slwa.wa.gov.au/documentSummary;dn=944337023084338;res=IELIND |via=[[State Library of Western Australia]] access to [[RMIT Informit|Informit]] |registration=yes}}</ref>{{Rp|57}} the responsibility of the prison itself lay with the superintendent.<ref name="Stevenson 1983 In the 1890s" />{{rp|44}}<ref name="Saunders 1960 Prison system" />{{rp|29}}

=== Officers ===
On convict ships, the convicts were guarded by [[Pensioner Guards|pensioner guards]], who were soldiers awarded pensions for their service in areas such as China, Crimea, and Afghanistan. Some remained in the military, but many opted to stay in the colony as settlers, having brought their wives and children with them.<ref>{{cite web|author1=State Library of Western Australia|title=Pensioner Guards|url=http://www.slwa.wa.gov.au/dead_reckoning/government_archival_records/n-s/pensioner_guards|website=Dead Reckoning|publisher=Government of Western Australia|accessdate=21 November 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221175823/http://www.slwa.wa.gov.au/dead_reckoning/government_archival_records/n-s/pensioner_guards|archivedate=21 February 2014 |deadurl=no|date=15 September 2011}} {{Cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6UF21fFcf |archivedate=21 November 2014}}</ref> The pensioner guards were expected to help deal with any incidents of unrest at the prison.<ref name="Saunders 1960 Prison system" />{{rp|12}}

Fremantle Prison's officers were known as warders until the early 20th century.<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|169}} They lived in specially built [[terrace houses]] within walking distance of the prison, and their lives were just as regimented as the prisoners.<ref name="Bosworth 2004 Convict Fremantle" />{{rp|17–24}} In the 1890s warders still had stringent living and working conditions, including ten- to twelve-hour working days.<ref name="Stevenson 1983 In the 1890s" />{{rp|65–67}} Due to a high turnover rate, many had little knowledge of either official policies or unofficial rules and traditions.<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" /> The warder's role, previously unwritten, only became clearly defined in 1902.<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|172–173}} As well as guarding against escapes and enforcing discipline, they oversaw prisoner work and instructed inmates in trades. The warders were also supposed to be moral role models for prisoners, while maintaining a formal, distant, relationship.<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|182}}

The prison officer's role in the 20th century did not change much, with the job still entailing a boredom-inducing daily routine focused on security.<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|189}} Officer training became a priority under Campbell's administration, from the late 1960s. Training courses were set up for staff inductions and promotions, and seminars were started for senior officers.<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|58, 61}} The most significant change in this period, however, was that prison officers achieved representation through the [[Western Australian Prison Officers' Union]].<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|189}} The strength of the union was based on the ability to almost cripple the prison system through [[strike action]], first taken in 1975.<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|190–191}}

=== Prisoners ===
{{See also|Convict era of Western Australia}}
[[File:Fremantle Prison inmates and main front Iwel jpeg convert.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.4|Prisoners in front of Main Cell Block, {{circa|1971}}]]
Convicts were introduced into Western Australia for three main purposes: inexpensive labour, additional labour, and an injection of British government spending into the local economy. During the initial years of transportation, convicts were generally young, from a rural background, and of good character, having only committed minor offences<ref name="Gibbs 2001 Archaeology" />{{rp|60–61}} – potential future colonists, after their sentence had been served.<ref name="Bosworth 2004 Convict Fremantle" />{{rp|74}} By the 1860s the majority were older, more serious offenders from urban areas,<ref name="Gibbs 2001 Archaeology" />{{rp|61}} including [[political prisoner]]s<ref name="FP Fenians" /> considered to be "difficult and dangerous".<ref name="Bosworth 2004 Convict Fremantle" />{{rp|76}} Following the transfer of Fremantle Prison to local control in 1886, it became Western Australia's primary prison.<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|71}} In the late 1880s and 1890s the number of inmates swelled dramatically. This increase predominantly comprised prisoners serving shorter sentences of under three months.<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|71}} The number of inmates in 1897 was 379, and Inspector of Prisons James Roe viewed the prison as "inconveniently full".<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|86}}

Despite a large expansion of the prison system, the problem of overcrowding remained throughout the 20th century, as did Western Australia's high incarceration rate relative to the rest of Australia.<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|86, 99}} The nature of prisoners changed, with three times the proportion of 16- to 19-year-olds in 1984 compared to 1898, and a growing over-representation of [[Aboriginal Australians|Aboriginal]] prisoners to nearly half the incarcerated population.{{refn|Of the total prison population, the proportion of [[Aboriginal Australians|Aboriginal]] prisoners was 5.4% in 1910, 16% in 1968, more than 30% in 1977, and at least 45% in 1982.<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|89}}|group = lower-alpha}}<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|88–89}} Sentences also increased in length, such that in 1984 more than 80% of inmates were serving more than a year.<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|94}} In the 1970s and 1980s, there was an increasing number of people committed for violent crimes, but still a minority of the population. Both staff and prisoners, however, perceived a notable increase in violence during these years, coinciding with the rise of illegal drugs in prison, and of sentences for drug-related offences.<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|95–97}}

== Prison operation ==
[[File:Freo prison WMAU gnangarra-146.jpg|thumb|Daily routine in 1991]]

=== Routine ===
In the Convict Establishment of 1855, the day began with the wakeup bell at 4:30 am, and the officers and prisoners assembled in the parade ground at 5:25 am. Prisoners were sent to work before and after breakfast (in their cells), before assembling for muster at midday. This was followed by dinner in the exercise yard or the work site, and more work throughout the afternoon, until supper at 6:00 pm in the cells. Night officers took over at 7:15 pm.<ref>{{cite web |author1=The Department of Finance – Building Management and Works |title=Convict Daily Life |url=http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/schoolgroups/educationalresources/Documents/FP%20Convict%20Daily%20Life.pdf |format=PDF |website=Fremantle Prison |publisher=Government of Western Australia |accessdate=15 September 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140205213722/http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/schoolgroups/educationalresources/Documents/FP%20Convict%20Daily%20Life.pdf |archivedate=5 February 2014 |deadurl=no}} {{Cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6TXKQYqbz |archivedate=23 October 2014}}</ref>
The transfer of the Convict Establishment to the colonially-run Fremantle Prison saw little change, and no new regulations.<ref name="Stevenson 1983 In the 1890s" />{{rp|29}}

A similar routine, but with fewer working hours, is described in the 1930s:
{{quote|<nowiki />
The following routine is observed by
those who go to Fremantle Jail:— 6.15
am., warning bell; prisoners rise and
fold beds. 6.30. officers muster and
unlock cells. 7.0.{{sic}} breakfast, which
lasts 15 minutes, after which men assemble
in their respective exercise yards.
7.55, parade for work. 11.45, parade
for dinner, after which men are in yard
until 1 pm, parade for work; 4.45 parade
for tea. 5.30. muster; all cells, etc.,
locked for the night. 7.55. warning
bell; prisoners to bed. 8.0,{{sic|nolink=y}} lights out
except as provided for in reformatory regulations.<nowiki />
|Eddie Dunstan|''The Daily News'' reporter<ref name="Daily News 1931">{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article83898268 |title=Life In Fremantle Jail |newspaper=[[Daily News (Perth, Western Australia)|The Daily News]] |location=Perth |date=13 June 1931 |accessdate=29 September 2014 |page=8 |edition=Home (semi-final) |via=[[NLA Trove|Trove]] (National Library of Australia)}}</ref>}}

Not much had changed by the 1960s. The day began with a waking bell at 6:45&nbsp;am. After a prisoner count, they moved into the yard until 7:30, when they collected breakfast and headed back to their cells. The 8:00 bell signaled a parade, and then the start of work, which lasted until 11:15. They ate a meal, locked in their cells until 12:20&nbsp;pm, followed by some time in the yards. At 1:00 there was another parade, and another session of work which lasted to 4:15. Another meal was collected, and prisoners were locked away in their cells overnight. The lights stayed on until 9:30&nbsp;pm. On the weekends the routine featured no work, and included a film played for the prisoners.<ref name="Stokes 1968 Human geography thesis" />{{rp|14–15}}

=== Diet ===
Prisoners ate meals in their cells, from the early years of the prison<ref name="Bosworth 2004 Convict Fremantle" />{{rp|49}} through to its closure in 1991.<ref name="Ayris 2003 Brief History" />{{rp|7}} Bread from the prison bakehouse was included in every meal in the convict era. It was served with black tea for breakfast, and with either tea or cocoa in the evening. The main meal, called dinner, was in the middle of the day, and also featured soup, meat, and vegetables.<ref name="Bosworth 2004 Convict Fremantle" />{{rp|59–60}}
By the 1890s food was still very limited in variety, with few vegetables. Porridge was given for breakfast, usually too fluid or overly solid, and the general standard of the prison's food was quite low,<ref name="Stevenson 1983 In the 1890s" />{{rp|84}} particularly in 1897 and 1898. However, the quality soon improved, as noted by the 1898 Royal Commission,<ref name="Stevenson 1983 In the 1890s" />{{rp|92}} which recommended decreasing rations to reduce costs.<ref name="Stokes 1968 Human geography thesis" />{{rp|4}}

In the 1960s, food preparation was overseen by a qualified chef, who also trained prisoners. The diet consisted of quality food, but "without trimmings".<ref name="Stokes 1968 Human geography thesis" />{{rp|7}} Breakfast was porridge, with a third of a pint of milk, a hot drink (tea, unless the prisoner bought{{refn|group=lower-alpha|Prisoners were paid for the work they did, and allowed to spend a small amount each year. The pay rate ranged from 50 cents to $1.60 per week in 1968,<ref name="Stokes 1968 Human geography thesis" />{{rp|15}} while the average weekly earnings in Western Australia for 1967–68 was $62.50<ref>{{cite web |last1=Archer |first1=K. E. |title=Average Weekly Earnings, September Quarter 1968 |url=http://www.ausstats.abs.gov.au/ausstats/free.nsf/0/CAB953CDA4F5F674CA25751600114E89/$File/63020_SEP1968.pdf |publisher=Commonwealth Bureau of Census and Statistics |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6UGvKP87S|archivedate=22 November 2014 |deadurl=no |format=PDF |date=25 November 1968}}</ref>}} coffee or cocoa), and either [[Vegemite]], honey, or margarine, depending on the week. Lunch and dinner had more variation. Both meals consisted of a meat dish – corned beef, sausages, or mince pie – as well as mashed potato and cabbage, although there was occasionally a [[roast dinner]].<ref name="Stokes 1968 Human geography thesis" />{{rp|7–8}} Meat, vegetables and bread were still a prominent part of the diet in 1991.<ref name="Ayris 2003 Brief History" />{{rp|7}}

=== Labour ===
As well as being used to build the prison itself, convict labour, with convicts in [[chain gang]]s, was used for other public works in the Fremantle and surrounding Perth area, including [[The Causeway]], [[Perth Town Hall]] and [[Stirling Highway]].<ref name="Ayris 2003 Brief History" />{{rp|33–34}}
The work undertaken by a convict depended on their behaviour and demeanour. Upon arrival to Western Australia, convicts were kept within the prison for a period of observation. If found to have a reasonable disposition, the convict would be sent to work, in a gang under the control of a warder. Typical activities included "quarrying, filling swamps, burning lime, constructing public buildings, roads and jetties"<ref name="Gibbs 2001 Archaeology" />{{rp|61}} around Fremantle and Perth.<ref name="Gibbs 2001 Archaeology" />{{rp|61}}

After some time, they might be sent to work on road or other projects away from these main settlements.<ref name="Gibbs 2001 Archaeology">{{cite journal |last1=Gibbs |first1=Martin |title=The Archaeology of the Convict System in Western Australia |journal=Australasian Historical Archaeology |date=2001 |volume=19 |pages=60–72 |url=http://0-search.informit.com.au.catalogue.slwa.wa.gov.au/documentSummary;dn=200204953;res=IELAPA |via=[[State Library of Western Australia]] access to [[RMIT Informit|Informit]] |registration=yes |issn=1322-9214}}</ref>{{rp|61}} Continued good behaviour could see the convict granted a ticket-of-leave, allowing private employment in a specified district of the colony, and eventually a Conditional Pardon, allowing most freedoms, except for returning to England. A Certificate of Freedom would only be granted at the end of a sentence. Misbehaviour would result in demotion through these levels of work, including returning to convict status within the prison. Re-offenders and captured escapees, after [[corporal punishment]] and time in solitary confinement, would be placed on a chain gang undertaking hard labour, typically on roads near Fremantle.<ref name="Gibbs 2001 Archaeology" />{{rp|61}}

Outside work, mostly on public infrastructure, continued beyond the convict era, but gradually declined due to discipline concerns, the rise of trade unions that saw such work as "a threat to free labour",<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|151}} and an increasing emphasis on work as rehabilitation rather than punishment.<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|151–152}} By 1911 outside work had all but ceased,<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|156}} but could not adequately be replaced by employment within the prison walls; a lack of suitable work plagued the prison throughout its lifetime.<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|149}} Work in the 19th century consisted of cooking, washing clothes, cleaning the prison, tailoring, bootmaking, and printing.<ref name="Bosworth 2004 Convict Fremantle" />{{rp|49}} However, demand exceeded the availability of such work – increasingly so in the later years of the 19th century – so prisoners were also given activities with no practical value other than keeping them occupied. These included breaking stones, operating a water pump, and [[oakum]] picking.<ref name="Georgiou 1995 Work and reform" />{{rp|8}} Even with these extra activities, by 1899, 60 to 70 men<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|156}} were employed at the pump, each doing only a few minutes work per hour, and occupied the rest of the time with recreation such as [[draughts]].<ref name="Saunders 1960 Prison system" />{{rp|17}}

New workshops built in 1901 allowed prisoners to work in bootmaking and tailoring, and from 1904, printing.<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|145–146}} Only a small fraction of prisoners were allocated to the workshops – 35 out of an average of 279 prisoners in 1902.<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|151}} In 1908, there were still few men employed in the workshops, 20 in tailoring, 15 in bootmaking, and 12 in mat making, with only half of these working at a time, and little improvement by the 1911 Royal Commission.<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|155–156}} The 20th century saw little change in the work prisoners did. There were similar workshops, with the addition of metal work, and similar jobs around the prison complex, including in the laundry, in the kitchen, and cleaning the prison.<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|160–161}} In 1984, 90% of prisoners were reported to be employed, either full-time or part-time. The meaningfulness of the work was nominal, as work was viewed as "a management option rather than [for] production",{{refn|group=lower-alpha|According to the superintendent in 1983<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|161}}}}<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|161}} but security concerns and discipline restricted the rehabilitative value of the work,<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|164}} and limited much of the work to jobs non-existent outside of prison.{{refn|group=lower-alpha|Examples included "making paper bags, tailoring and heaping wood"<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|161}}}}<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|161}}

=== Punishments ===
[[File:FremantletPrisonWhippingPost 2005 SeanMcClean.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Post prisoners were tied to when flogged]]
In the convict era, particularly during Hampton's term as governor, misbehaving prisoners were punished with [[flogging]], solitary confinement, and working in chain gangs at gunpoint.<ref name="Saunders 1960 Prison system" />{{rp|12}} Particularly difficult prisoners were put to work hand pumping groundwater into the prison's reservoir. Known as cranking, it was especially despised by the prisoners.<ref name="Ayris 2003 Brief History" />{{rp|31}} Staff disliked giving the lashings – in 1851, out of a total of 400 lashings ordered, 150 were remitted as the superintendent could not find anyone to undertake the task. The role was so disliked that inducements were offered, including extra pay or improved lodgings.<ref name="Bosworth 2004 Convict Fremantle">{{cite book |last1=Bosworth |first1=Michal |title=Convict Fremantle: A Place of Promise and Punishment |year=2004 |publisher=University of Western Australia Press |isbn=978-1-920694-33-3}}</ref>{{rp|24}}

By the 1880s, punishments also included a restricted diet of bread and water (for a short time span), time in [[leg irons|irons]], and a lengthening of a prisoner's sentence by a visiting magistrate.<ref name="Saunders 1960 Prison system" />{{rp|16,18}} The [[cat o' nine tails]], which had been used since the early days of the prison,<ref name="Ayris 2003 Brief History" />{{rp|31}} was abolished during the post-1911 Royal Commission reforms.<ref name="Saunders 1960 Prison system" />{{rp|23}} Other reforms in this period saw the number of punishments inflicted decrease from 184 in 1913 to 57 in 1914, and 35 in 1915.<ref name="Saunders 1960 Prison system" />{{rp|25}}

Flogging was discontinued in the 1940s, with the last incident occurring in 1943.<ref name="Bosworth 2004 Convict Fremantle" />{{rp|52}} From that decade, punishments were decided by the superintendent after hearing the case against a prisoner, or by a magistrate for grievous violations. Lesser transgressions could result in solitary confinement, or restriction from visitors, education, and concerts; serious offences were punishable by the cancellation of any remission earned and a bread-and-water diet, normally over a two-week period.<ref name="Saunders 1960 Prison system" />{{rp|30}}

=== Executions ===
{{further|List of executions at Fremantle Prison|Capital punishment in Australia}}

[[File:FremantlePrisonGallows1.jpg|thumb|right|upright|The gallows, last used in 1964]]
As soon as Fremantle Prison came under local control in 1886, a refractory block with gallows was planned.<ref name="Ayris 2003 Brief History" />{{rp|46}} It was completed in 1888,<ref name=HEWA /> and first used in 1889 to execute a convicted murderer, Jimmy Long, a Malayan.<ref name="Ayris 2003 Brief History" />{{rp|46}}<ref>{{cite news|url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/ndp/del/article/32717229|title=Execution in Fremantle Prison|newspaper=The Western Mail|date=9 March 1889|page=8<!--From scanned image. Trove has the page incorrectly listed as 18-->|accessdate=5 December 2014}}</ref> The gallows room was the only lawful place of [[Capital punishment|execution]] in Western Australia between 1888 and 1984.{{refn|group=lower-alpha|Capital punishment was abolished in Western Australia in 1984<ref name=HEWA />}}<ref name=HEWA /> At least 43 men{{refn|group=lower-alpha|[[Cyril Ayris]] claims 46 men were executed,<ref name="Ayris 2003 Brief History" />{{rp|63}} while other sources claim 43 were executed<ref name="Bosworth 2004 Convict Fremantle" />{{rp|91–92}}<ref name=HEWA /><ref name="FP capital punishment">{{cite web |author1=The Department of Finance – Building Management and Works |title=Capital Punishment |url=http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/History/themodernera/capitalpunishment/Pages/default.aspx |website=Fremantle Prison |publisher=Government of Western Australia |accessdate=10 October 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140513025417/http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/History/themodernera/capitalpunishment/Pages/default.aspx |archivedate=13 May 2014 |deadurl=no}} {{Cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6TXKRF8b8 |archivedate=23 October 2014}}</ref>}} and one woman were hanged in this period. [[Martha Rendell]] was the only woman to be hanged at the prison, in 1909. The last person to be hanged was serial killer [[Eric Edgar Cooke]], executed in 1964.<ref name="Ayris 2003 Brief History" />{{rp|63}}

From the day of sentencing to death, prisoners were kept in a concrete-floored cell in New Division. They were vigilantly observed to prevent them escaping their sentence through suicide. With hangings taking place on Monday mornings, at 8:00&nbsp;am, condemned prisoners were woken three hours earlier, and provided with a last meal, shower, and clean clothes. Afterwards, handcuffed, they were moved to a holding or "condemned cell" nearby the gallows, and allowed a couple of sips of brandy to calm their nerves. Shortly before 8:00&nbsp;am, they were hooded, led up to the execution chamber, which could hold as many as eleven witnesses, stood over the trap door, had a noose put around their neck, and were hanged by dropping through the opening trap door. After medical examination, the deceased was removed for burial.<ref name="Ayris 2003 Brief History" />{{rp|54–56}}

=== Escapes ===
There were a multitude of attempted escapes from Fremantle Prison. Prominent escapees included [[Moondyne Joe]] in 1867, [[John Boyle O'Reilly]] in 1869 and six other [[Fenian]]s in 1876, and [[Brenden Abbott]] in 1989.<ref name=HEWA>{{cite book |last1=Murray |first1=Sandra |editor1-last=Gregory |editor1-first=Jenny |editor2-last=Gothard |editor2-first=Jan |title=Fremantle Prison |work=Historical Encyclopedia of Western Australia |date=2009 |publisher=University of Western Australia Press |isbn=978-1-921401-15-2 |pages=391–2}}</ref>

==== Moondyne Joe ====
{{Main article|Moondyne Joe}}
[[File:FremantleprisonMoondynescell.JPG|thumb|left|upright|alt=Cell with walls and floor covered in Jarrah, held with an abundance of nails|Moondyne Joe's "escape-proof" cell]]
Joseph Bolitho Johns, better known as Moondyne Joe, was Western Australia's best known [[bushranger]]. In July 1865, Johns was sentenced to ten years penal servitude for killing a steer.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article3753477 |title=Supreme Court—Criminal Side |newspaper=[[The Perth Gazette and West Australian Times]] |date=7 July 1865 |accessdate=3 June 2014 |page=3 |via=Trove (National Library of Australia)}}</ref><ref name="Elliot 1978 Moondyne Joe" />{{rp|41–43}}  He and another prisoner absconded from a work party in early November, and were on the run for nearly a month, during which time Johns adopted the nickname Moondyne Joe.<ref name="Elliot 1978 Moondyne Joe" />{{rp|44–45, 47}} For absconding and for being in possession of a firearm, Moondyne Joe was sentenced to twelve months in irons, and transferred to Fremantle Prison.<ref name="Elliot 1978 Moondyne Joe">{{cite book |last1=Elliot |first1=Ian |title=Moondyne Joe: The Man and the Myth |origyear=First published: Nedlands, Western Australia: University of Western Australia Press, 1978 ISBN 0-85564-130-4 |year=1998 |location=Carlisle, Western Australia |publisher=Hesperian Press |isbn=0-85905-244-3}}</ref>{{rp|49–50}} In July 1866 he received a further six months in irons for trying to cut the lock out of his door, but in August Moondyne Joe succeeded in escaping again.<ref name="Elliot 1978 Moondyne Joe" />{{rp|54–56}} Moondyne Joe formulated a plan to escape the colony by travelling overland to South Australia, but was captured on 29 September about {{convert|300|km|mi}} north-east of [[Perth]].<ref name="Elliot 1978 Moondyne Joe" />{{rp|59, 66–67, 81}}

As punishment for escaping and for the robberies committed while on the run, Moondyne Joe received five years hard labour on top of his remaining sentence.  Extraordinary measures were taken to ensure that he did not escape again. He was transferred to Fremantle Prison where a special "escape-proof" cell was made for him, built from stone, lined with [[Eucalyptus marginata|jarrah]] [[Railroad tie|sleepers]] and over 1000 nails. In early 1867 Moondyne Joe was set to work breaking stone, but rather than permit him to leave the prison,<ref name="Elliot 1978 Moondyne Joe" /> the acting comptroller-general<ref name="Ayris 2003 Brief History" />{{rp|37}} ordered that the stone be brought in and dumped in a corner of the prison yard, where Moondyne Joe worked under the constant supervision of a warder.<ref name="Elliot 1978 Moondyne Joe" />

Governor [[John Hampton]] was so confident of the arrangements, he was heard to say to Moondyne Joe: "If you get out again, I'll forgive you". However, the rock broken by Moondyne Joe was not removed regularly, and eventually a pile grew up until it obscured the guard's view of him below the waist. Partially hidden behind the pile of rocks, he occasionally swung his sledgehammer at the limestone wall of the prison. On 7 March 1867, Moondyne Joe escaped through a hole he had made in the prison wall.<ref name="Elliot 1978 Moondyne Joe" />{{rp|86–89}} A few days before the second anniversary of his escape, Moondyne Joe was recaptured, returned to prison, and sentenced to an additional four years in irons. Eventually, Governor [[Frederick Weld]] heard of his predecessor Hampton's promise, and decided that further punishment would be unfair. Moondyne Joe was given a ticket of leave in May 1871.<ref name="Elliot 1978 Moondyne Joe" />{{rp|111–113, 165–166}}{{clear left}}

==== The Fenians ====
{{Main article|Catalpa rescue}}
[[File:Fenians escape Fremantle.jpg|thumb|Fenians escape by whaleboat to ''Catalpa'']]
From 1865 to 1867, British authorities rounded up supporters of the [[Irish Republican Brotherhood]], or Fenians, an [[Ireland|Irish]] independence movement, and transported sixty-two of them to Western Australia.<ref name="FP Fenians" /> In 1869, John Boyle O'Reilly escaped on the American whaling ship ''Gazelle''<ref>{{cite book |title-link=s:Page:Life of John Boyle O'Reilly.djvu/118 |title=Life of John Boyle O'Reilly |others={{icon|Wikisource}} |last=Roche |first=James Jeffrey |editor-last=O'Reilly |editor-first=Mary |year=1891 |publisher=Cassell |location=New York |via=Wikisource |page=82}} {{cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=https://archive.org/details/cu31924022146645 |archivedate=14 December 2007}}</ref> and settled in Boston. Later that year, pardons were issued to many of the imprisoned Fenians, after which only eight militant Fenians remained in Western Australia's penal system.<ref name="FP Fenians">{{cite web |author1=The Department of Finance – Building Management and Works |title=The Fenians |url=http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/History/theconvictera/characters/thefenians/Pages/default.aspx |website=Fremantle Prison |publisher=Government of Western Australia |accessdate=11 October 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140512214853/http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/History/theconvictera/characters/thefenians/Pages/default.aspx |archivedate=12 May 2014 |deadurl=no}} {{Cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6TXKS2BmX |archivedate=23 October 2014}}</ref>

The Fenians in America bought the whaling ship ''Catalpa'', which on 29 April 1875 sailed from [[New Bedford, Massachusetts]] on a secret rescue mission. Coordinating with local Fenian agents, the escape was arranged for 17 April 1876, when most of the Convict Establishment garrison would be watching the Royal Perth Yacht Club [[regatta]]. ''Catalpa'' dropped anchor in [[international waters]] off [[Rockingham, Western Australia|Rockingham]] and dispatched a [[whaleboat]] to the shore. At 8.30 am, six Fenians who were working in work parties outside the prison walls absconded, and were met by carriages that raced {{convert|50|km}} south to where the boat was waiting.<ref name="FP Fenians" />

The whaleboat managed to rendezvous with ''Catalpa'' the following day, which then headed out to sea. They were chased by the steamship ''[[SS Georgette]]'', which had been commandeered by the colonial governor.<ref name="FP Fenians" /> Though ''Georgette'' caught up with the whaler on 19 April, ''Catalpa''{{'s}} master claimed they were in international waters, and that an attack on ''Catalpa'' would be considered an [[Casus belli|act of war]] against the United States. Not wanting to cause a diplomatic incident, ''Georgette'' allowed ''Catalpa'' to flee.<ref name="FP Fenians" />

==== Brenden Abbott ====
{{Main article|Brenden Abbott}}
Brenden Abbott, "the Postcard Bandit", escaped from Fremantle Prison in 1989. He had been sentenced to twelve years in prison for "Australia's first 'drop in'-style bank robbery"<ref name="Australian Story 2003 Usual Suspect" /> at the [[Belmont, Western Australia|Belmont]] branch of the [[Commonwealth Bank]]. While working in the prison's tailor shop, he was able to stitch together overalls resembling those worn by the guards. Abbott and two accomplices took the opportunity to escape, wearing the overalls, when left unsupervised in the workshop. They cut through a bar and got onto the roof. One accomplice fell and broke his leg, but Abbott and the other managed to jump over to the wall, and thus escape.<ref name="Australian Story 2003 Usual Suspect">{{cite web |last1=Jones |first1=Caroline |title=The Usual Suspect |url=http://www.abc.net.au/austory/content/2003/s978408.htm |work=[[Australian Story]] |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |accessdate=6 November 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131216215802/http://www.abc.net.au/austory/content/2003/s978408.htm |archivedate=16 December 2013 |deadurl=no |format=transcript |date=27 October 2003}} {{Cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6TsWPu1eN |archivedate=6 October 2014}}</ref>

Abbott avoided capture until 1995, committing various robberies as he moved across Australia.<ref name="ABC News 2013 Search continues">{{cite news |last1=Martin |first1=Lucy |title=Search Continues for Long Term Prison Escapees |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-06-04/police-hunt-long-time-prison-escapees/4732448 |accessdate=6 November 2014 |work=ABC News |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |date=4 June 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130612035509/http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-06-04/police-hunt-long-time-prison-escapees/4732448 |archivedate=12 June 2013 |deadurl=no}} {{Cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6TsZ1Q3ss |archivedate=6 November 2014}}</ref> He also escaped from a Queensland prison after two years<ref name="Australian Story 2003 Usual Suspect" /> and returned to Western Australia, allegedly robbing the Commonwealth Bank's [[Mirrabooka, Western Australia|Mirrabooka]] branch.<ref name="7.30 Report 2005 Postcard Bandit" /> Abbott was recaptured in Darwin, six months after his escape,<ref name="Australian Story 2003 Usual Suspect" /> and was sent to a Queensland maximum-security prison<ref name="ABC News 2013 Search continues" /> with a twenty year sentence to serve.<ref name="7.30 Report 2005 Postcard Bandit">{{cite web |last1=O'Donnell |first1=Mick |title=Postcard Bandit Hopes for Transfer to WA |format=transcript |url=http://www.abc.net.au/7.30/content/2005/s1409562.htm |work=The 7.30 Report |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |accessdate=6 November 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130613223406/http://www.abc.net.au/7.30/content/2005/s1409562.htm |archivedate=13 June 2013 |deadurl=no |date=7 July 2005}} {{Cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6Tsb9D1y0 |archivedate=6 November 2014}}</ref>

=== Riots ===
{{Main article|Riots at Fremantle Prison}}
There have been various prisoner riots and other disturbances at Fremantle Prison over the years that it was operational.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Starick |first1=Chloe |title=Torchlight Fright at Fremantle Prison |url=http://3degree.ecu.edu.au/articles/2666 |accessdate=27 October 2014 |work=3rd Degree |volume=8 – Semester 2, 2009 |edition=2 |publisher=Edith Cowan University |date=28 August 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141026150008/http://3degree.ecu.edu.au/articles/2666 |archivedate=26 October 2014 |deadurl=no}} {{Cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6TcAdRyWg |archivedate=26 October 2014}}</ref> One of the earliest was in 1854,<ref name="SMH 1854">{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12956418 |title=Western Australia |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=20 February 1854 |accessdate=27 October 2014 |page=4 |via=Trove (National Library of Australia)}}</ref> while major riots which occurred in 1968 and 1988<ref>{{cite book |author1=Policy and Planning Unit |title=Predicting Major Prison Incidents |date=May 1990 |publisher=Office of Corrections |location=Victoria |via=[[Australian Institute of Criminology]] |url=http://www.criminologyresearchcouncil.gov.au/reports/12-87.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=14 November 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140212001236/http://www.criminologyresearchcouncil.gov.au//reports/12-87.pdf |archivedate=12 February 2014 |deadurl=no}} {{Cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6U4Bvng8A |archivedate=14 November 2014}}</ref>{{rp|28}} resulted in damage to the prison.<ref name="Stokes 1968 Human geography thesis" /><ref name="Farrington 2007 Max Sec" />

==== 1968 ====
A riot occurred on 4 June 1968, precipitated by the serving of allegedly contaminated food to prisoners the previous evening. Other factors that contributed were the rudimentary and deplorable state of sanitation and personal cleanliness facilities, tougher sentencing introduced with the Parole Act of 1964, and the overcrowding. When the work bell was rung at 1 pm, prisoners rebelled; refusing to go back to work, they assembled themselves in the exercise yards. The prison superintendent Mr Thorpe negotiated with two deputations of prisoners. As well as better food, they demanded single cells and the dismissal of specific wardens.<ref name="Stokes 1968 Human geography thesis" />

After approximately three hours, the negotiations broke down, and that night's evening meal was withheld. That caused the prisoners to riot, breaking fittings; during the commotion, three prison officers, three prisoners, and a detective sustained injuries. Additional police and wardens arrived at 5 pm, but took seven hours to subdue the prisoners, with the last of them locked in their cells just after midnight. The extent of the damage was in the order of $200 to $300. To relieve the overcrowding and reduce prisoner agitation, around 60 men who had not taken part in the riot were transferred to prisons at Albany, Geraldton, [[Karnet Prison Farm|Karnet]], and Barton's Mill. However, other improvements could not be undertaken without funding from the [[Brand–Nalder Ministry|state government]], which did not consider prison reform a priority.<ref name="Stokes 1968 Human geography thesis">{{cite thesis |degree = M.A.|first = Nancy P.|last = Stokes|title = Human Geography Thesis on Fremantle Prison|publisher = [[Graylands Teachers College]]|date = November 1968|url = http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/21750802?q=+&versionId=26151783}}</ref>

==== 1988 ====
{{Main article|Fremantle Prison riot}}
On 4 January 1988, despite the {{convert|42|C}} heat,<ref name="Garton-Smith 2000 CVM">{{cite journal |last1=Garton-Smith |first1=Jennifer |editor1-last=Witcomb |editor1-first=Andrea |title=Commemoration, Voices and Museums |journal=Open Museum Journal |date=January 2000 |volume=1 |url=http://hosting.collectionsaustralia.net/omj/vol1/pdfs/gsmith.pdf <!--metadata from: http://hosting.collectionsaustralia.net/omj/vol1/gartonsmith.html --> |format=PDF |accessdate=25 September 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141021081309/http://hosting.collectionsaustralia.net/omj/vol1/pdfs/gsmith.pdf |archivedate=21 October 2014 |deadurl=no |publisher=Australian Museums and Galleries Online |via=Collections Australia Network |issn=1443-5144}} {{Cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6TXKW5pJH |archivedate=23 October 2014}}</ref> officers decided prisoners should remain outside in the exercise yards in the afternoon. As division 3 prisoners were let inside at around 4&nbsp;pm, a voice exclaimed "Let's take 'em",<ref name="Ayris 2003 Brief History" />{{rp|59}} and simultaneously, guards were splashed with boiling water, usually used for making tea.<ref name="Garton-Smith 2000 CVM" />{{rp|5}} A horde of prisoners stormed the cellblock, attacking the guards with whatever makeshift weapons they could find.<ref name="Ayris 2003 Brief History" />{{rp|59}} This resulted in pandemonium; prisoners rushed along landings, overpowering officers and taking them hostage, while at the same time, other prisoners darted between cells, starting fires. The prisoners withdrew to the exercise yard, taking six<ref name="WA Police">{{cite web|author1=Western Australia Police Media and Public Affairs|title=Episodes in Western Australia's Policing History|url=http://www.police.wa.gov.au/LinkClick.aspx?link=PDFs/Episodes_WAPolicingHistory.pdf|publisher=Government of Western Australia|accessdate=24 August 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150701112831/http://www.police.wa.gov.au/LinkClick.aspx?link=PDFs/Episodes_WAPolicingHistory.pdf|archivedate=11 July 2015 |deadurl=no|page=19|date=2006}} {{cite archives |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6b1Dryp3k#.pdf |archivedate=24 August 2015}}</ref> hostages, as flames quickly overran the building, spread into the rafters, and caused the roof to collapse.<ref name="Ayris 2003 Brief History" />{{rp|59–60}}

Police negotiators communicated with the ring leaders,<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|20}} and by nightfall only five hostages remained.<ref name="Ayris 2003 Brief History" />{{rp|60}}
Meanwhile, the fire brigade had trouble bringing the inferno in the main cell block under control, as the prison's gate was too narrow for their trucks, and prisoners impeded their endeavours by throwing debris at them.<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|20}}
The prisoners' leaders made three demands: a meeting with Attorney General [[Joseph Berinson]], access to the media, and a guarantee of no retribution afterwards. The next morning, after 19 hours, the hostages were released, even though only the third demand had been met.<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|20}} Prisoners did, however, have an opportunity to communicate with the press during the siege, as the riot was a live media event with television helicopters filming from overhead.<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|20}}

Although there were no deaths,<ref name="Garton-Smith 2000 CVM" />{{rp|6}} the fire caused $1.8&nbsp;million of damage,<ref name="Farrington 2007 Max Sec">{{cite book |last1=Farrington |first1=Karen |title=Maximum Security |date=2007 |publisher=Arcturas |location=London |isbn=978-0-572-03386-6 |page=<!-- e-book: no page number given --> |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wsSrBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT144}}</ref> and officers were injured.<ref name="Garton-Smith 2000 CVM" />{{rp|6}} In the aftermath of the riot, there was extensive media attention on Fremantle Prison, and investigative journalists uncovered prior warnings to the prison authorities of the risk of such an event. The government hastily initiated an enquiry into the incident, and a report was completed within six weeks.<ref name="Megahey 2000 Community apart" />{{rp|20–22}}
A trial involving thirty-three prisoners charged over the riot was also held, the largest in the state's history, which resulted in lengthened sentences for the prisoners.<ref name="Ayris 2003 Brief History" />{{rp|61}}

== Conservation ==
[[File:RestoredGatehouse.jpg|thumb|
The newly restored prison gatehouse in 2005
]]

=== Heritage listing ===
Fremantle Prison was listed in the Western Australian Register of Historic Places as an interim entry on 10 January 1992 and included as a permanent entry on 30 June 1995.<ref name="AHDB" /> Described as the best preserved convict-built prison in the country, it became the first building in Western Australia to be listed on the [[Australian National Heritage List]], in 2005. The Australian Federal Heritage Minister, Senator [[Ian Campbell (Australian politician)|Ian Campbell]], stated that it would be included in a nomination of eleven convict areas to become [[World Heritage Site]]s.<ref>{{cite web |date=1 August 2005 |title=Fremantle Prison WA's First National Heritage Listing |work=Archived Media Releases and Speeches |url=http://www.environment.gov.au/minister/archive/env/2005/mr01aug305.html |publisher=Department of the Environment, Commonwealth of Australia |archiveurl=http://pandora.nla.gov.au/pan/67588/20071024-0001/www.environment.gov.au/minister/env/2005/mr01aug305.html |archivedate=24 October 2007 |deadurl=no |accessdate=7 October 2014}} {{Cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6TXHZ80Wi |archivedate=23 October 2014}}</ref> Five years later, these locations were inscribed on the UNESCO [[World Heritage List]] in 2010 as the [[Australian Convict Sites]].<ref name="World Heritage ABC">{{cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2010/08/01/2970125.htm |title=World Heritage Status for Fremantle Prison |publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] |date=1 August 2010 |accessdate=1 August 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140813030425/http://www.abc.net.au/news/2010-08-01/world-heritage-status-for-fremantle-prison/927578 |archivedate=13 August 2014 |deadurl=no}} {{Cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6TXHdU3ai |archivedate=23 October 2014}}</ref>

The process of obtaining World Heritage listing focused historical interpretation and conservation efforts on the prison's convict era. This came at the expense of its more recent history, included use as an internment centre during World War II, and the imprisonment of Aboriginal prisoners. The prioritisation, evident from the first [[Conservation Plan|conservation plans]] from before the prison closed, is reflected in the branding of the tourist experience as "Fremantle Prison – the Convict Establishment", and through restorations that, while necessary to prevent damage and deterioration, strip away the site's recent history.<ref name="Witcomb 2012 tensions world heritage">{{cite journal |last1 = Witcomb|first1 = Andrea|title = Tensions Between World Heritage and Local Values: The Case of Fremantle Prison (Australia)|year = 2012|work = World Heritage Papers|volume = 31|department = Community Development Through World Heritage|editor1-last = Albert|editor1-first = Marie-Theres|editor2-last = Richon|editor2-first = Marielle|editor3-last = Viñals|editor3-first = Marie José|editor4-last = Witcomb|editor4-first = Andrea|display-editors = 3|publisher = United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO)&nbsp;– World Heritage Centre|location = Paris, France|url = http://whc.unesco.org/document/117040|format = PDF|accessdate = 13 October 2014|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140829222225/http://whc.unesco.org/document/117040|archivedate = 29 August 2014|deadurl = no|isbn = 978-92-3-001024-9}} {{Cite additional archived pages |archiveurl = http://www.webcitation.org/6TXHtVWpx|archivedate = 23 October 2014}}</ref>

=== Restoration ===
Various parts of Fremantle Prison have had restoration works undertaken since the 1990s; a total of $800,000 was spent between 1996/97 and 1998/99<ref>{{cite hansard |jurisdiction=Western Australia |title=Fremantle Prison, Restoration Work |url=http://www.parliament.wa.gov.au/hansard/hans35.nsf/(ATT)/21A70E7082A59FEB482567A9001EFA9E/$file/A0701038.PDF |format=PDF |accessdate=23 October 2014 |house=[[Western Australian Legislative Assembly|Legislative Assembly]] |date=1 July 1999 |page=9986 |speaker=[[Mike Board]] |position=Minister for Works |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141023133830/http://www.parliament.wa.gov.au/hansard/hans35.nsf/(ATT)/21A70E7082A59FEB482567A9001EFA9E/$file/A0701038.PDF |archivedate=23 October 2014 |deadurl=no}} {{Cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6TXWLxE79 |archivedate=23 October 2014}}</ref> on works which included restoring the facade of the Anglican chapel.<ref>{{cite web |title=Fremantle Prison's Chapel Gets a Helping Hand |url=http://www.environment.gov.au/minister/archive/env/97/mr27julwa97.html |website=Archived Media Releases and Speeches |publisher=Commonwealth of Australia |accessdate=23 October 2014 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6TXWPsD24 |archivedate=23 October 2014 |deadurl=no |date=27 July 1997}} {{cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=http://pandora.nla.gov.au/pan/67588/20070202-0000/www.environment.gov.au/minister/env/97/mr27julwa97.html |archivedate=2 February 2007}}</ref>
In 2005, work was undertaken on the restoration of the prison gatehouse area. Non-original rendering was removed and the original stonework was revealed.<ref name="ausmed" />
Work was also completed on the tunnels during 2005/06,<ref name="The West 2006 tunnel work" /> and the main cell block was restored with an eighteen month, $1.9 million<ref>{{cite news |last1=Scourfield |first1=Stephen |title=WA Tourism Awards |work=The West Australian |date=10 November 2007 |at=Travel: p.&nbsp;20}}</ref> project in 2006 and 2007.<ref>{{cite web |title=Minister to Welcome Two Millionth Visitor to Fremantle Prison |url=http://www.mediastatements.wa.gov.au/pages/StatementDetails.aspx?listName=StatementsCarpenter&StatId=1926 |website=Media Statements |publisher=Government of Western Australia |accessdate=23 October 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141023140954/http://www.mediastatements.wa.gov.au/pages/StatementDetails.aspx?listName=StatementsCarpenter&StatId=1926 |archivedate=23 October 2014 |deadurl=no |date=24 December 2007}} {{Cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6TXYPbd5v |archivedate=23 October 2014}}</ref> The gallows room was restored in 2013 to conditions at the time of the last execution, in 1964.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Emery|first1=Kate|title=Jail's Chilling Past Is Restored|url=https://au.news.yahoo.com/thewest/a/19114318/jails-chilling-past-is-restored/|accessdate=23 October 2014|work=The West Australian|date=26 September 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141023141841/https://au.news.yahoo.com/thewest/a/19114318/jails-chilling-past-is-restored/ |archivedate=23 October 2014 |deadurl=no}} {{Cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6TXYoxVXw |archivedate=23 October 2014}}</ref>

== Tourism ==
{{external media
