[[File:FremantlePrisonWalsh1.JPG|thumb|left|upright|Drawing found in James Walsh's cell]]
The Fremantle Prison Collection contains around 15,000 items associated with the prison's site, history, or the experiences of its workers and prisoners.<ref>{{cite web |author1=The Department of Finance – Building Management and Works |title=The Fremantle Prison Collection |url=http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/Cultural_Heritage/prisoncollection/Pages/default.aspx |website=Fremantle Prison |publisher=Government of Western Australia |accessdate=12 August 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140513024824/http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/Cultural_Heritage/prisoncollection/Pages/default.aspx |archivedate=13 May 2014 |deadurl=no}} {{Cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6TXORCYKd |archivedate=23 October 2014}}</ref> It is also involved in preserving [[oral history|oral histories]], with interview transcripts stored at Fremantle Prison and recordings archived in the [[Battye Library]] Oral History Collection. Recollections have been recorded since 1989, and include the experiences of authorities, staff, volunteer visitors, and prisoners.<ref>{{cite book |author1=Towards Federation 2001 |editor1-last=Woods |editor1-first=Martin |title=Australia's Oral History Collections: A National Directory |date=1992 |publisher=National Library of Australia |location=Canberra |isbn=0-642-28148-3 |pages=201–2 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3x0nxQv6llgC&pg=PA201 |accessdate=12 October 2014}}</ref> The Fremantle Prison records and collections, including archaeological, provide a substantial resource for researchers.<ref name=AHDB />

The Prison Gallery showcases and offers for sale the artworks of current and ex-prisoners of Western Australia. It also hosts other exhibits related to the history of the prison, including historical artefacts.<ref name="FP gallery">{{cite web |author1=The Department of Finance – Building Management and Works |title=Prison Gallery |url=http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/Cultural_Heritage/conservation/projects/prisongallery/Pages/default.aspx |website=Fremantle Prison |publisher=Government of Western Australia |accessdate=21 October 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130429200515/http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/Cultural_Heritage/conservation/projects/prisongallery/Pages/default.aspx |archivedate=29 April 2013 |deadurl=no}} {{Cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6TXOSUKLg |archivedate=23 October 2014}}</ref> Many cells and areas of the prison depict prisoners' artwork,<ref name="Ayris 2003 Brief History" />{{rp|29}} including that of the 19th-century forger [[James Walsh (convict)|James Walsh]], whose artwork was hidden beneath layers of white-wash for decades.<ref name="Bosworth 2004 Convict Fremantle" />{{rp|50}} Painting or drawing on walls was originally forbidden,<ref name="Bosworth 2004 Convict Fremantle" />{{rp|50}} though graffiti, which could be viewed as art or vandalism, occurred throughout the prison's operational years.<ref name="Palmer 1997 graffiti">{{cite journal |last1=Palmer |first1=Daniel |title=In the Anonymity of a Murmur: Graffiti and the Construction of the Past at the Fremantle Prison|journal=Studies in Western Australian History |date=1997 |volume=17 |pages=104–115 |url=http://0-search.informit.com.au.catalogue.slwa.wa.gov.au/documentSummary;dn=980303146;res=IELAPA |via=State Library of Western Australia access to [[RMIT Informit|Informit]] |registration=yes |accessdate=7 November 2014 |issn=0314-7525}}</ref>{{rp|106–107}} This rule was relaxed in special cases<ref>{{cite web |author1=The Department of Finance – Building Management and Works |title=Fremantle Prison Art Tour |url=http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/Visit_Us/tours/arttour/Pages/default.aspx |website=Fremantle Prison |publisher=Government of Western Australia |accessdate=6 November 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106041719/http://www.fremantleprison.com.au/Visit_Us/tours/arttour/Pages/default.aspx |archivedate=6 November 2014 |deadurl=no}} {{Cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6TsDwsmxr |archivedate=6 November 2014}}</ref> – including, from 1976, long-term prisoners within their own cells – but only for work considered art and not graffiti.<ref name="Palmer 1997 graffiti" />{{rp|107}} Art, or [[art therapy]], was not officially permitted until the 1980s;<ref name="Bosworth 2004 Convict Fremantle" />{{rp|50}} graffiti was never formally permitted, but in the prison's last six months, with closure imminent, the rule was not enforced.<ref name="Palmer 1997 graffiti" />{{rp|107}}{{refn|An archaeological study found almost 800 graffiti images.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-11-12/fremantle-convict-prison-graffiti-reveals-hardships-of-jail-life/8015230|title=Fremantle Prison graffiti reveals daily hardships of life behind bars|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|author=Erin Parke|date=12 November 2016|accessdate=12 November 2016}}</ref>|group = lower-alpha}}

A more contemporary prison artist was Dennis (NOZ) Nozworthy, who stated that he found art on death row, in 1982.{{Efn|Capital punishment was abolished in 1984;<ref name=HEWA /> Nozworthy spent 22 years in prison<ref name=Nozworthy />}} Some of his work currently is held in the collections of [[Curtin University]], [[Perth Central TAFE]], and the WA Government, Department of Justice.<ref name=Nozworthy>{{cite web |last1=Nozworthy |first1=Dennis |title=Prison: Life and Death |url=http://www.pica.org.au/art05/noz-prison05.html |publisher=Perth Institute of Contemporary Arts |accessdate=6 February 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060823024311/http://pica.org.au/art05/noz-prison05.html |archivedate=23 August 2006}} {{Cite additional archived pages |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6TXOV0zkU |archivedate=23 August 2006}}</ref>
Other cells contain [[Indigenous Australians#Art|Aboriginal]] artwork, many by unknown artists. The [[Walmajarri language|Walmajarri]] artist [[Jimmy Pike]] started painting in Fremantle prison, having received tuition from Steve Culley and David Wroth.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Kleinert |first1=Sylvia |chapter=Revisiting the Prison: Museums in a Penal Landscape |year=2006 |title=20th International Congress of Historical Sciences |location=Sydney |publisher=University of NSW Press |page=1 |chapter-url=http://espace.cdu.edu.au/view/cdu:2440 <!--Trove URL: http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/185625845 --> }}</ref>
{{clear}}

